    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Cell Phones on the Road</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Mary D Federico letter says having speakerphone conversation while driving is no less distracting than talking with passenger in car (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Oct. 7 letter writer who called for disallowing the use of cell phones, including speakerphones, while driving has taken the discussion to a point of absurdity. Yes, the ban on hand-held use makes sense, and yes, driving is an activity that should demand our full attention.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Oct. 7 letter writer who called for disallowing the use of cell phones, including speakerphones, while driving has taken the discussion to a point of absurdity. Yes, the ban on hand-held use makes sense, and yes, driving is an activity that should demand our full attention.</p>
        <p>But why is having a conversation by speakerphone any more distracting than having one with a passenger? Should we insist on ''no talking'' trips? And what should we do about the ultimate in distractions: children bickering in the back seat?</p>
        <p>Let's be realistic and shoot for a federal act banning hand-held use.</p>
        <p>MARY D. FEDERICO  New York, Oct. 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
